div.h1: Temperature Scaling Effect on Softmax Distributions

div.p: Temperature (T) is a hyperparameter that controls randomness in token selection. Applied BEFORE softmax, not after.
These represent unnormalized scores from the model's final layer. Higher values = model's preferred tokens.

ul.li: Almost all probability on highest logit
Use for: factual tasks, code generation

div.p: Key Insight: Temperature controls the "entropy" of the output distribution.

ul.li: Low T: Reduces entropy confident, deterministic outputs
High T: Increases entropy diverse, creative outputs

div.p: The mathematical effect: Division by T scales the difference between logits. Large T small differences soft softmax. Small T large differences hard softmax.
Gradient Effect: Higher T produces smoother gradients during backpropagation, which can help training stability (used in label smoothing / knowledge distillation).
